 a growing debate, the authors argue that traditional technocratic ways of designing policy are inadequate to cope with increasingly complex challenges, and suggest co-production as a more democratic alternative. Drawing on 12 compelling international contributions from practitioners, policy makers, activists and actively engaged academics, ideas of power are used to explore how genuine democratic involvement in the policy process from those outside the elites of politics can shape society for the better. The authors present insights on why and how to generate change in policy processes, arguing for increased experimentation in policy design. The book will be a valuable resource for researchers and students in public policy, public administration, sociology and politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPolicy sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aBartley, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlume, Toby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBracy, Fawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurall, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Hillary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCórdova, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDowns, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzales, Moises, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Cory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaldipur, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHassan, Prakriti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowell, Michaela, econtributor.4ctb